\begin_layout Standard
Neutrinos in the SM are electrically neutral, massless particles categorized
 into three generations based on their charged, more massive Lepton cousins.
 They are believed to follow the free-particle Dirac Equation which is given
 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[i\hbar\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}-mc\right]\psi=0\label{eq:diraceqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{0}=\begin{bmatrix}I_{2} & 0\\
0 & -I_{2}
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{x}\\
-\sigma_{x} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{y}\\
-\sigma_{y} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{3}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{z}\\
-\sigma_{z} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:gammamatrices}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 identity matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x,y,z}$
\end_inset

 are the Pauli Spin matrices, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{0}=\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t,\partial_{1}=\partderiv x,\partial_{2}=\partderiv y,\partial_{3}=\partderiv z.\label{eq:fourderivative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The solutions to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diraceqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are called Dirac spinors and can be written in terms of left-handed (LH)
 and right-handed (RH) components.
 Any spinor can be decomposed in LH and RH projections using a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

chiral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi=\left(\hat{O}_{\text{LH}}+\hat{O}_{\text{RH}}\right)\psi.\label{eq:chiralprojections}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The chiral operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}_{\text{LH,RH}}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:chiralprojections"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{O}_{\text{LH}}\psi=\frac{1}{2}(I_{4}-\gamma^{5})\psi=\psi_{\text{LH}}\quad\hat{O}_{\text{RH}}\psi=\frac{1}{2}(I_{4}+\gamma^{5})\psi=\psi_{\text{RH}}\label{eq:chiraloperators}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{4}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 identity matrix,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{5}=i\gamma^{0}\gamma^{1}\gamma^{2}\gamma^{3}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & I_{2}\\
I_{2} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:gammafivedef}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\text{LH,RH}}$
\end_inset

 are LH and RH chiral spinors.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:chiraloperators"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the Dirac Equation then becomes after some manipulation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}i\hbar\left(\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t-\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}\right)\psi_{\text{RH}} & =m\gamma^{0}\psi_{\text{LH}}\\
i\hbar\left(\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t+\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}\right)\psi_{\text{LH}} & =m\gamma^{0}\psi_{\text{RH,}}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:diraceqnchiral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}=\sum_{i=1}^{3}\sigma_{i}\nabla_{i}.\label{eq:matrixdotproduct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the limiting case of vanishing mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m\rightarrow0\right)$
\end_inset

, as in the SM, the equations decouple.
 We now have enough information to make two very important insights about
 neutrinos in the SM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first important fact is that a neutrino spinor is always LH in weak
 interactions.
 That is to say a weakly interacting neutrino is LH and antineutrino is
 RH as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:chiraloperators"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 There are no mechanisms in the SM for RH neutrinos and LH antineutrinos.
 If we also distribute 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:chiraloperators"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and examine each term under parity transformation, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a vector (by definition) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{5}\psi$
\end_inset

 is a axial (pseudo)vector.
 This vector minus axial (V-A) construction is what allows for parity and
 charge-parity (CP) violation with weak interactions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second important insight is that the chirality and helicity of the neutrino
 the same for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 Helicity is the projection of a particle's spin vector on its momentum
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}=\frac{\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\mathbf{P}}{\left|\mathbf{P}\right|}\label{eq:helicityoperator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

 is the momentum of the particle.
 For a free, massless neutrino in the momentum basis, the Dirac Equation
 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\left(\frac{E}{c}-\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}\right)\psi_{\text{RH}} & =0\\
\left(\frac{E}{c}+\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}\right)\psi_{\text{LH}} & =0.
\end{aligned}
\quad\left[\text{Momentum basis}\right]\label{eq:diraceqnchiralmassless}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diraceqnchiralmassless"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 commutes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left([A,B]=AB-BA\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\text{LH,RH}}$
\end_inset

 are eigenstates of the helicity operater with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Neutrino Oscillations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neutrino oscillations were not a known phenomenon when neutrinos were incorporat
ed into the Standard Model.
 Outstanding problems were arising as the expected flux of neutrinos from
 the Sun and atmosphere were too small.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first indication of neutrino oscillations was from the Ray Davis Homesteak
 Mine experiment which began in the 1960s.
 Ray Davis was an expert Chemist and designed a radiochemical experiment
 to measure the flux of neutrinos from Sun.
 The purpose of this experiment was to test John Bahcall's prediction of
 the fusion rate in and neutrino flux from the Sun.
 Measurements continued into the 1980s and showed that the flux of neutrinos
 as measured at Homesteak was about 1/3 the expected rate and became known
 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Solar Neutrino Problem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Ultimately vindicated by the confirmation of neutrino oscillations, the
 Homesteak Mine measurements helped establish the Standard Solar Model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another outstanding problem emerged with measurements of atmospheric neutrinos,
 in particular muon and electron types.
 Atmospheric neutrinos are produced when cosmic rays strike the atmosphere.
 These collisions generate neutrinos through different decay channels.
 In total the ratio of muon to electron neutrinos should equal 2:1, but
 there was observed deficit in muon type neutrinos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Two Flavor Derivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The phenomenon of neutrino oscillations can be described with elementary
 Quantum Mechanics.
 Beginning with the Schrödinger Equation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:schroeqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}-\frac{\hbar}{i}\partderiv t\diracket{\nu(\mathbf{r},t)} & =\hat{H}\diracket{\nu(\mathbf{r},t)}\end{aligned}
\label{eq:schroeqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}$
\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian for the physical system.
 If we consider a massive neutrino of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 in its rest frame (free particle), the Hamiltonian becomes diagonal which
 acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $\diracket{\nu_{j}}$
\end_inset

 results in the eigenvalue equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{H}\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t)}=E_{j}\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t)}\label{eq:schroeqntimeindep}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the energy of the neutrino 
\begin_inset Formula $\diracket{\nu_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 If we substitute 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:schroeqntimeindep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:schroeqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\diracket{\nu(\mathbf{r},t)}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the following
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t)}=e^{-iE_{j}t/\hbar}\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t=0)}\label{eq:schroeqnsolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t=0)}$
\end_inset

 is created with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 at the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The time-independent solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:schroeqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is a plane-wave given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t=0)}=e^{i\mathbf{p}\cdot\mathbf{r}/\hbar}\diracket{\nu_{j}}.\label{eq:schroeqnsolutiontimeindep}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Before being able to describe neutrino oscillations, we must define our
 basis states.
 For this example, consider that there are only two eigenstates, labeled
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

, in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mass
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 basis with definite mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 However, experiments can produce neutrinos, as well as probe them, only
 of definite 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flavor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, denoted by a Greek letter subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Let the generated neutrino, which is a linear superposition of mass states
 1 and 2, have momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 and flavor 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Since both mass eigenstates share the same momentum momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 (but not energy!), the exponential term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:schroeqnsolutiontimeindep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is an overall phase that will cancel out later.
 We can postulate a linear transformation, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, between the basis states given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:pmnstwodimgen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}\nu_{\alpha}\\
\nu_{\beta}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}U_{11} & U_{12}\\
U_{21} & U_{22}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\nu_{1}\\
\nu_{2}
\end{bmatrix}\label{eq:pmnstwodimgen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This linear transformation must be a unitary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U^{-1}=U^{\dagger},\dagger=\text{transpose conjugate}\right)$
\end_inset

 since the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 constitute a complete orthonormal set in the mass basis.
 With this unitary property, we can imagine 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 as a rotation matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}\nu_{\alpha}\\
\nu_{\beta}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rr}
\cos(\theta) & \sin(\theta)\\
-\sin(\theta) & \cos(\theta)
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\nu_{1}\\
\nu_{2}
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:pmnstwodimangle}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle between the two bases.
 We can imagine this transformation between bases as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:twoflavorrotation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 If we create a neutrino of flavor 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and observe it after a time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=T>0$
\end_inset

, then the probability of observing it as flavor 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\neq\alpha$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

